.TH HOSTER 1 "August 2024" "hoster 1.10.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
hoster \- project-scoped /etc/hosts management
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B hoster
.RI [ --verbose | -v ]
.RI [ --help ]
.RI [ --version ]
.IR command
.RI [ args... ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B hoster
keeps a project's
.I /etc/hosts
entries inside the repository, scoped per environment
.RB ( lcl ", " dev ", " hlg ", " prd ),
and applies them on demand. Every contributor sees the same host pairs
alongside the code and can swap them in and out of the system hosts
file with one command.
.PP
The system hosts file is resolved at runtime from
.B $OSTYPE:
.I /private/etc/hosts
on macOS,
.I /etc/hosts
on Linux,
.I /c/Windows/System32/drivers/etc/hosts
under Git Bash / MSYS / MinGW.
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B init
Create an empty
.I .hosts
repository in the current folder, populated with empty
.IR hosts.lcl ", " hosts.dev ", " hosts.hml ", " hosts.prd .
.TP
.B add \fIIP HOSTNAME \fR[\fI--ENV\fR]
Append an entry to the named environment's host file. If the IP is
malformed
.B hoster
exits non-zero with an
.B INVALID IP
message.
.TP
.B remove \fIHOSTNAME \fR[\fI--ENV\fR]
Delete a matching entry from the environment's host file. Matching is
anchored on whitespace, so
.I www.example.com
will not over-delete
.IR www.example.com.staging .
Has
.B rm
as an alias.
.TP
.B list \fR[\fI--ENV\fR]
Print the entries for one environment, or for all four if no flag is
given. Each block is preceded by a banner with the environment name.
.TP
.B edit \fR[\fI--ENV\fR]
Open the environment's host file in the configured editor.
.TP
.B apply \fI--ENV\fR
Insert the environment's block into the system hosts file. If the
project already has a block applied, it is replaced atomically through
a temp file. Requires
.BR sudo .
.TP
.B clean \fI--ENV\fR
Reverse of
.BR apply :
remove the project's block from the system hosts file. A no-op with a
message when nothing is applied. Requires
.BR sudo .
.TP
.B status
Scan the system hosts file for the current project's marker blocks
and print the list of environments currently applied.
.TP
.B diff \fI--ENV\fR
Read-only preview of what
.B apply
would change. Extracts the currently-applied block for the named
environment and runs
.BR diff (1)
against the project's environment file. If nothing is applied yet,
prints the project file as the "would-add" preview.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B --verbose, -v
Surface internal
.B run_cmd
invocations on stderr. Consumed in place before the subcommand,
so it can appear anywhere on the line.
.TP
.B --help, --H
Print the common-commands help and exit.
.TP
.B --version, --V
Print the installed version (read from
.IR hoster.version )
and exit.
.SH ENVIRONMENT FLAGS
.TP
.B --dev, -d
Development hosts (\fIhosts.dev\fR).
.TP
.B --hlg, -h
Homologation hosts (\fIhosts.hml\fR).
.TP
.B --lcl, -l
Local hosts (\fIhosts.lcl\fR).
.TP
.B --prod, -p
Production hosts (\fIhosts.prd\fR).
.SH FILES
.TP
.I .hosts/hosts.{lcl,dev,hml,prd}
Per-environment host entries, versioned alongside the project.
.TP
.I /etc/hosts
.PD 0
.TP
.I /private/etc/hosts
.TP
.I /c/Windows/System32/drivers/etc/hosts
.PD
System hosts file resolved at runtime via
.BR $OSTYPE .
.SH EXAMPLES
Initialise a project and apply its development hosts:
.PP
.RS
.EX
$ hoster init
$ hoster add 10.0.0.1 api.dev.example.com --dev
$ hoster apply --dev
.EE
.RE
.PP
List every environment, then clean up:
.PP
.RS
.EX
$ hoster list
$ hoster status
$ hoster clean --dev
.EE
.RE
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR hosts (5),
.BR sudo (8)

